WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.660
Next month, he's running 100K through the woods of British Columbia, and he grew up

00:00:06.660 --> 00:00:10.920
in New York City, so he's hoping that as a city boy he doesn't get mauled by a bear.

00:00:10.920 --> 00:00:12.320
Please welcome Dan.

00:00:12.320 --> 00:00:18.959
All right, so I'm here to talk to you about moving to Quarto from RMarkdown or Python

00:00:18.959 --> 00:00:23.080
Jupyter Notebooks, so hello everyone.

00:00:23.080 --> 00:00:27.660
But before we get started, I would first like to acknowledge that we are currently on the

00:00:27.660 --> 00:00:34.220
unsucceeded land of the Munsee and the Lenape people.

00:00:34.220 --> 00:00:35.220
And I'm Daniel.

00:00:35.220 --> 00:00:38.700
I'm currently a postdoctoral research and teaching fellow at the University of British

00:00:38.700 --> 00:00:41.060
Columbia up in Vancouver.

00:00:41.060 --> 00:00:46.500
I'm from New York City, but I moved up there over a year ago, and I'm currently a data

00:00:46.500 --> 00:00:47.939
science educator at Posit.

00:00:47.939 --> 00:00:55.939
I got all of my teaching background from the Carpentries, and I also authored a book about

00:00:55.939 --> 00:00:58.580
pandas in Python.

00:00:58.580 --> 00:01:03.540
But this talk is about literate programming, which is the ability for you to write code

00:01:03.540 --> 00:01:09.440
and write regular prose text and interweave it together in a single document or a report.

00:01:09.440 --> 00:01:15.980
It also allows you to write slide decks like we've learned from Emil earlier today, and

00:01:15.980 --> 00:01:20.900
also this talk is also written in Quarto, which is also another form of literate programming

00:01:20.900 --> 00:01:23.720
that I'm going to be talking to you about today.

00:01:23.720 --> 00:01:26.080
So literate programming, who would use it?

00:01:26.080 --> 00:01:27.080
Why would you want to use it?

00:01:27.080 --> 00:01:32.199
So as a data scientist, you may or may not have learned or used R Markdown or Jupyter

00:01:32.199 --> 00:01:40.199
Notebooks, and for people like us, it's really good for doing analysis or reports and documentation.

00:01:40.199 --> 00:01:43.480
If you're also an academic, you can write your papers in it.

00:01:43.480 --> 00:01:48.300
I sort of have this project that maybe I'll try to translate my dissertation into Quarto

00:01:48.300 --> 00:01:50.519
and just see how well the tool works.

00:01:50.519 --> 00:01:53.080
That's sort of what I want to try it out for.

00:01:53.440 --> 00:01:57.519
But even as a technical writer, you can use it for not just Quarto, but just literate

00:01:57.519 --> 00:01:58.720
programming in general.

00:01:58.720 --> 00:02:02.720
You can use it to write blogs or websites or presentations or books and all of that

00:02:02.720 --> 00:02:03.720
stuff.

00:02:03.720 --> 00:02:08.339
So that whole realm of content is called literate programming.

00:02:08.339 --> 00:02:12.839
As R users, we probably have heard or used a tool called R Markdown.

00:02:12.839 --> 00:02:19.320
It's been around for many, many years, and I'll give you a...

00:02:19.320 --> 00:02:23.720
If you don't know about R Markdown, then this is sort of the main component of an R

00:02:23.720 --> 00:02:28.880
Markdown document, where you have three backticks, a set of curly braces, the letter R, and then

00:02:28.880 --> 00:02:34.639
in here, in your regular document, you get to write regular R code as if it was in your

00:02:34.639 --> 00:02:38.940
console or in a script or right in R Studio.

00:02:38.940 --> 00:02:46.000
And this gives you the ability to take that R code and write regular prose text with it.

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:50.559
So I can have a regular Markdown header that says, like, here's a section about loading

00:02:50.559 --> 00:02:55.279
data, here's some regular text about what the dataset is, and here's the code to load

00:02:55.279 --> 00:02:56.279
the data.

00:02:56.279 --> 00:03:04.199
Up at the top, I have some metadata information about what the title would be, what type of

00:03:04.199 --> 00:03:05.199
output.

00:03:05.199 --> 00:03:06.960
So right now, I'm picking an HTML output.

00:03:06.960 --> 00:03:11.199
You can set it to PDFs or other forms of output as well.

00:03:11.199 --> 00:03:14.899
And then there's also some things that you just have to do or load, but you don't really

00:03:14.899 --> 00:03:16.699
want to be part of the report.

00:03:16.699 --> 00:03:20.580
So you have the ability to still run code, but sort of turn off the output so no one

00:03:20.580 --> 00:03:22.779
really sees it in your final report.

00:03:22.779 --> 00:03:27.179
So that's the main part of an R Markdown document.

00:03:27.179 --> 00:03:33.960
And what we can do is we can take that regular R code or that document that you just saw,

00:03:33.960 --> 00:03:38.100
and you can run a command right in your command line called rscript, and you can run this

00:03:38.100 --> 00:03:42.100
function called render from the Markdown library.

00:03:42.100 --> 00:03:45.059
And what it will do is then generate the format that you asked for.

00:03:45.059 --> 00:03:47.940
So in the previous example, you saw I asked for an HTML output.

00:03:47.940 --> 00:03:52.979
Running this code will give me a HTML file of that code.

00:03:52.979 --> 00:03:57.100
I talk a lot about project formats and project templates.

00:03:57.100 --> 00:04:01.619
So what I also like to do is specify like, hey, when you generate this HTML output, please

00:04:01.619 --> 00:04:05.100
put it in the output folder so I don't end up with a folder with 50 files all in one

00:04:05.100 --> 00:04:06.619
go.

00:04:06.619 --> 00:04:10.039
And you end up with a file that looks like this during that output.

00:04:10.039 --> 00:04:12.919
So here's the longer form of that type of analysis.

00:04:12.919 --> 00:04:17.839
I'm loading data, filtering data, saving, doing some tidying stuff, plotting, and then

00:04:17.839 --> 00:04:18.839
fitting a model.

00:04:18.839 --> 00:04:22.200
And you get like a nice little report in here.

00:04:22.200 --> 00:04:27.959
And so I can have code, see its output, and write about it all in one go.

00:04:27.959 --> 00:04:29.559
But this talk is about Corto.

00:04:29.559 --> 00:04:33.480
So you can think of Corto as like the next iteration of R Markdown.

00:04:33.480 --> 00:04:35.600
R Markdown's not really going anywhere.

00:04:35.600 --> 00:04:41.200
But there was a lot of things learned during the development of R Markdown.

00:04:41.200 --> 00:04:45.519
And so Corto sort of encompasses all of the things that were learned and sort of tries

00:04:45.519 --> 00:04:46.640
to make it better.

00:04:46.640 --> 00:04:48.799
So it's still a plain text source document.

00:04:48.799 --> 00:04:55.679
So you can open it in any type of program that can read plain text files.

00:04:55.679 --> 00:04:58.160
It still does literate programming.

00:04:58.160 --> 00:05:00.640
Corto natively just has multi-language support.

00:05:00.640 --> 00:05:05.519
So you can have an R document, a Python document, or an R and Python document.

00:05:05.519 --> 00:05:11.519
It also out-of-the-box supports Julia and Observable for JavaScript.

00:05:11.519 --> 00:05:16.279
And you can take a Corto document, very similar to R Markdown, and generate multiple outputs.

00:05:16.279 --> 00:05:23.119
So PDFs, HTML files, anything else that I can't think of because I don't really use.

00:05:23.119 --> 00:05:25.440
And that's all because it's built on top of Pandoc.

00:05:25.440 --> 00:05:29.079
So you can write regular Markdown, and then it can generate out into something a little

00:05:29.079 --> 00:05:30.679
bit prettier.

00:05:30.679 --> 00:05:34.679
And the nice thing about it, about Corto, at least from my end and maybe a lot of people

00:05:34.679 --> 00:05:38.279
here at this conference, is that it's just more familiar because it's coming from the

00:05:38.279 --> 00:05:39.799
R Markdown world.

00:05:39.799 --> 00:05:45.720
So hopefully, you don't have to do that much more work to get using Corto if you are already

00:05:45.720 --> 00:05:48.720
using R Markdown.

00:05:48.720 --> 00:05:58.079
So we can actually use Corto to render the same exact R Markdown file.

00:05:58.079 --> 00:06:02.480
And we'll get a nice little piece of output that looks like this.

00:06:02.480 --> 00:06:03.880
So it's really similar.

00:06:03.880 --> 00:06:06.000
The formatting is a little bit different.

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:10.040
You'll see at the bottom, I added the ability to just put in a table of contents.

00:06:10.040 --> 00:06:13.040
And so you get a nice little table of contents on the side instead of at the top.

00:06:13.040 --> 00:06:15.440
So as I scroll, it's kind of always there with us.

00:06:15.440 --> 00:06:20.079
So that's one of the nicer things that comes out of the box compared to something like

00:06:20.079 --> 00:06:23.600
R Markdown.

00:06:23.600 --> 00:06:27.519
But there's a couple of differences if we actually want to create a Corto document,

00:06:27.519 --> 00:06:31.000
like a .qmd instead of .rmd.

00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:36.399
In the YAML header, really the only thing we need to change is instead of output HTML

00:06:36.399 --> 00:06:39.440
document, it's now format HTML.

00:06:39.440 --> 00:06:42.799
And a lot of the other bits and pieces, there are some overlaps or some new things.

00:06:42.799 --> 00:06:46.239
Some things get taken out, et cetera, et cetera.

00:06:46.239 --> 00:06:52.000
The other thing about Corto and R Markdown documents, I forgot the exact version of R

00:06:52.000 --> 00:06:53.000
Markdown.

00:06:53.000 --> 00:06:57.119
But you can now take all of those command line chunk options and actually put them in

00:06:57.119 --> 00:06:59.700
line using this hash pipe.

00:06:59.700 --> 00:07:05.220
And then you can now have all of those options as a comment in your code.

00:07:05.220 --> 00:07:09.220
And that's really nice because if you start doing things like doing figure captions or

00:07:09.220 --> 00:07:13.700
alt text, the problem in the previous way was everything actually had to be in that

00:07:13.700 --> 00:07:15.019
first line.

00:07:15.019 --> 00:07:20.179
And things just ran off the screen, and it gets really hard, especially if you're using

00:07:20.179 --> 00:07:22.859
some version control system.

00:07:22.859 --> 00:07:27.380
So this sort of allows us to separate things out and make that part just a little bit nicer

00:07:27.380 --> 00:07:29.179
to work with.

00:07:29.179 --> 00:07:33.579
That's generally the only sets of changes that we need to make.

00:07:33.579 --> 00:07:38.660
And then from there, instead of telling Corto render to render the RMD document, we can

00:07:38.660 --> 00:07:41.619
just say, hey, I just created this QMD document.

00:07:41.619 --> 00:07:44.059
Can you go and output that as well?

00:07:44.059 --> 00:07:51.420
And the only sort of tricky thing about if you're just working with QMD files and you

00:07:51.420 --> 00:07:56.940
want to sort of have the output go into a different directory, you sort of have to do

00:07:56.940 --> 00:08:01.940
this thing where you turn the whole thing into a Corto project, and then the output

00:08:01.940 --> 00:08:06.299
directory and the output file formats you can sort of use.

00:08:06.299 --> 00:08:11.100
But if it's just a regular Corto document and you don't care about exactly what the

00:08:11.100 --> 00:08:16.260
file name and the file output is, you can just use plain old Corto render or sort of

00:08:16.260 --> 00:08:17.260
do this.

00:08:17.260 --> 00:08:23.660
I do this as this little hack where you just turn the whole project into a Corto project.

00:08:23.660 --> 00:08:27.260
So that's sort of like the little weird thing with using Corto documents.

00:08:27.260 --> 00:08:31.619
Only if you're trying to render individual Corto documents, it doesn't apply for websites

00:08:31.619 --> 00:08:35.619
or slides and stuff like that that use the Corto YAML file.

00:08:35.619 --> 00:08:38.739
And it just needs to exist for this whole process to work.

00:08:38.739 --> 00:08:40.900
So you don't have to put anything in that YAML file.

00:08:40.900 --> 00:08:43.340
It just sees the file and then is like, oh, it's a project.

00:08:43.340 --> 00:08:44.919
I know what to do now.

00:08:44.919 --> 00:08:49.239
But if you want to read more about this sort of issue or any developments, here's two links

00:08:49.239 --> 00:08:51.820
about the discussion.

00:08:51.979 --> 00:08:55.859
And then there's this other way where you can have a pre-render script or a post-render

00:08:55.859 --> 00:09:00.380
script that if you really want to move stuff around, you can sort of put that in your workflow

00:09:00.380 --> 00:09:02.640
as well.

00:09:02.640 --> 00:09:06.140
And that's all around this concept around project templates that I talk a lot about.

00:09:06.140 --> 00:09:10.739
So in DCR and NYR, I've given two talks about project templates.

00:09:10.739 --> 00:09:15.260
I've taught a course with Tiffany Timbers at UBC.

00:09:15.260 --> 00:09:16.580
It's DSci310.

00:09:16.580 --> 00:09:19.859
And it's around reproducible workflows for data science.

00:09:19.900 --> 00:09:23.460
And project templates are also another thing about it.

00:09:23.460 --> 00:09:25.419
So I really care about project templates.

00:09:25.419 --> 00:09:30.099
I'm the person, if I'm in your group project, I just deal with the file structure of it.

00:09:30.099 --> 00:09:31.659
And then I just make that.

00:09:31.659 --> 00:09:35.659
That's one of my things that I get really annoyed if it's not set up properly.

00:09:35.659 --> 00:09:38.340
So I usually end up handling that.

00:09:38.340 --> 00:09:39.340
OK.

00:09:39.340 --> 00:09:41.700
So Jupyter.

00:09:41.700 --> 00:09:45.820
If you've used Jupyter Notebooks, there's these two sort of talks.

00:09:45.820 --> 00:09:47.539
One that says, I don't like notebooks.

00:09:47.539 --> 00:09:52.599
And that's sort of stirred the boat a little bit.

00:09:52.599 --> 00:09:55.380
And then there was a follow-up discussion called, I'd like notebooks.

00:09:55.380 --> 00:09:59.659
And you'll have access to the slides, and you can actually watch those talks about the

00:09:59.659 --> 00:10:04.539
pros and cons of working with actual Jupyter Notebook files.

00:10:04.539 --> 00:10:08.580
But I think both of the speakers there, they do have a point.

00:10:08.580 --> 00:10:11.440
There are pros and cons with any tool that you use.

00:10:11.760 --> 00:10:16.640
Here's my list of what I agree with and what I don't agree with, or just my workings with

00:10:16.640 --> 00:10:19.960
Jupyter Notebooks, is that it's really good for technical writing.

00:10:19.960 --> 00:10:25.239
It does the whole literate program thing almost too much, because there's no easy way to hide

00:10:25.239 --> 00:10:26.359
certain bits of the output.

00:10:26.359 --> 00:10:29.520
You just see everything all the time, which is, for better or for worse, if you really

00:10:29.520 --> 00:10:32.280
want transparency, you have that option.

00:10:32.280 --> 00:10:35.840
But on the downside, at the end of the day, if you try to double-click the file, if you

00:10:35.840 --> 00:10:39.799
can even double-click the file, it's really just this giant JSON file.

00:10:39.799 --> 00:10:43.799
And that just makes version control kind of messy.

00:10:43.799 --> 00:10:48.320
But on the plus side, if you upload a Jupyter Notebook to GitHub, it automatically renders.

00:10:48.320 --> 00:10:50.760
So that's a really nice thing as well.

00:10:50.760 --> 00:10:55.940
Cordo documents and R Markdown documents, if you upload them to GitHub, it just gets

00:10:55.940 --> 00:10:58.640
rendered as just a plain text file.

00:10:58.640 --> 00:11:00.799
So Jupyter Notebooks, it's really nice.

00:11:00.799 --> 00:11:04.119
After a workshop, and I'm teaching at a Jupyter, it's just like, here's all my stuff, and I

00:11:04.119 --> 00:11:07.840
don't really have to think about making things prettier.

00:11:07.880 --> 00:11:11.239
This is exactly what happened in the workshop.

00:11:11.239 --> 00:11:16.080
For data science, the thing with Jupyter Notebooks is I sort of treat it more like an output

00:11:16.080 --> 00:11:20.080
format than a source document, or at least that's how most people use it, because all

00:11:20.080 --> 00:11:23.840
of the output and figures are all in the same document.

00:11:23.840 --> 00:11:29.080
So again, if you start using version control, you sort of end up in this scenario where

00:11:29.080 --> 00:11:35.799
you're now version controlling output of code and not just the raw source part of the code.

00:11:35.799 --> 00:11:38.280
So again, it's really nice for a workshop.

00:11:38.280 --> 00:11:45.859
You sort of run into issues or humps, speed bumps, as you're working in version control.

00:11:45.859 --> 00:11:49.320
But at UBC, we use this a lot, or Jupyter Notebooks a lot, in teaching.

00:11:49.320 --> 00:11:54.739
There's this tool called MBGrader, and it helps automate a lot of our student assignments

00:11:54.739 --> 00:11:55.739
and stuff like that.

00:11:55.739 --> 00:11:59.700
So there is a lot of tools, and there's an ecosystem around Jupyter Notebooks, so that's

00:11:59.700 --> 00:12:04.200
always really great, especially if you're a teacher.

00:12:04.200 --> 00:12:06.919
But again, I've talked about Jupyter Notebooks being JSON.

00:12:06.919 --> 00:12:12.039
Here's just the first two or three bits of the actual JSON.

00:12:12.039 --> 00:12:17.840
So you see some of the code bits, and here's the markdown of the thing, and then I tell

00:12:17.840 --> 00:12:20.599
it to give me the first five lines of the data set.

00:12:20.599 --> 00:12:25.840
So here's the HTML view, here's the actual plain text view, and then this is the actual

00:12:25.840 --> 00:12:26.840
code.

00:12:26.840 --> 00:12:34.440
So you can see it's really easy to accidentally delete a comma, especially if you're trying

00:12:34.440 --> 00:12:36.799
to deal with merge conflicts of some sort.

00:12:36.799 --> 00:12:38.760
And then the entire notebook doesn't even load.

00:12:38.760 --> 00:12:46.640
So there's a really high chance of just not looking at it in a dedicated notebook application,

00:12:46.640 --> 00:12:50.239
you're going to screw something up.

00:12:50.239 --> 00:12:55.080
So there are tools, VSCode on the left and JupyterLab on the right.

00:12:55.080 --> 00:12:58.919
There are now tools that, at least with VSCode, I can at least double-click the thing and

00:12:58.919 --> 00:12:59.919
just view it.

00:12:59.919 --> 00:13:04.640
With JupyterLab, you always have to make sure that Python's installed and running, all the

00:13:04.640 --> 00:13:12.719
tools are there, and then you have to be able to load it up, and then hopefully everything

00:13:12.719 --> 00:13:13.719
loads.

00:13:13.719 --> 00:13:18.840
But at least with VSCode, you have a chance to just look at the output without having

00:13:18.840 --> 00:13:23.280
to worry about if you have everything installed properly.

00:13:23.280 --> 00:13:26.840
But that's sort of the downside, because it's not really a plain text format.

00:13:26.840 --> 00:13:33.840
I still really need a dedicated tool to sort of just browse and look at a notebook, compared

00:13:33.840 --> 00:13:40.039
to a QMD file that's a markdown file, really, with some special bits of syntax in it.

00:13:40.039 --> 00:13:44.919
But this is sort of just what evolved in the Python ecosystem, and that's why it's super

00:13:44.919 --> 00:13:47.440
popular.

00:13:47.440 --> 00:13:51.880
And Jupyter does do R. You need the IR kernel that you can install, and then all of a sudden

00:13:51.960 --> 00:13:54.239
you get this nice little R notebook.

00:13:54.239 --> 00:14:00.119
So for those of you who are in a Python shop, but you know R, you can actually get this

00:14:00.119 --> 00:14:05.000
stuff installed and sort of integrate yourself into a Python team if you want, and still

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:10.239
have a thing that looks like a Python notebook until they open it, and it's like, what is

00:14:10.239 --> 00:14:11.960
going on here?

00:14:11.960 --> 00:14:15.840
But it is kind of nice, and we do this at UBC as well when we teach our intro data science

00:14:15.840 --> 00:14:16.840
course.

00:14:16.840 --> 00:14:21.719
We teach it in R, but using Jupyter notebooks.

00:14:22.559 --> 00:14:28.719
And so if you were to programmatically in the command line want to render a Python notebook,

00:14:28.719 --> 00:14:33.479
you can use Jupyter convert, and you can convert whether or not it's a Python notebook or an

00:14:33.479 --> 00:14:40.719
R notebook, and it will give you the HTML format, because that's what I asked for.

00:14:40.719 --> 00:14:46.039
And like I said, one of the things is I personally try to keep the Jupyter notebook as a source

00:14:46.039 --> 00:14:51.640
document, so one of the things I like to do is when I'm in my makefile or right before

00:14:51.640 --> 00:14:56.440
I'm going to check my code in, there's this option now to pass in clear output, and so

00:14:56.440 --> 00:15:01.719
you don't have to have the notebook open to sort of like kernel reset, kernel delete output.

00:15:01.719 --> 00:15:04.679
You can do this in the command line, which sort of gives you a lot more flexibility how

00:15:04.679 --> 00:15:05.679
you call this.

00:15:05.679 --> 00:15:11.599
And this way, at least if you're in a notebook flow, the inversion control, it's still just

00:15:11.599 --> 00:15:12.599
the source code.

00:15:12.599 --> 00:15:16.719
So if you're really like, I want to use notebooks all the time, this is sort of how you can

00:15:16.719 --> 00:15:20.559
reduce the amount of friction, especially if you're working with version control.

00:15:20.559 --> 00:15:24.119
And then if you really want the rendered output, you can turn the output to an actual

00:15:24.119 --> 00:15:30.840
notebook file, so you actually do have source and rendered version as part of your analysis

00:15:30.840 --> 00:15:32.919
or your project.

00:15:32.919 --> 00:15:35.599
But Quarto, again, can also work with notebooks as well.

00:15:35.599 --> 00:15:39.799
So your barrier of entry to using Quarto is really as simple as like calling Quarto render

00:15:39.799 --> 00:15:42.520
and then just passing in the Jupyter notebook file.

00:15:42.520 --> 00:15:45.520
It doesn't, by default, execute the code from top to bottom.

00:15:45.520 --> 00:15:48.359
It just says like, whatever is rendered in here, I'm going to dump it out.

00:15:48.359 --> 00:15:53.340
So if you really wanted to run the code from top to bottom, like kernel run all, you pass

00:15:53.340 --> 00:16:00.000
in this dash dash execute, and it will actually go and run the code out for you.

00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:06.919
And you end up with the Quarto version of a Jupyter notebook, looks something like this.

00:16:06.919 --> 00:16:10.200
And then the regular version of the Jupyter notebook looks like this.

00:16:10.200 --> 00:16:13.640
So really, it's the same amount of things, and you can see like here's actual Python

00:16:13.640 --> 00:16:28.159
code has like the Quarto template around it as well.

00:16:28.159 --> 00:16:31.880
And so this is just the code bits for like all of the extra stuff that I usually put

00:16:31.880 --> 00:16:32.880
in.

00:16:32.880 --> 00:16:39.599
So convert to an HTML, execute the code from top to bottom, add in a table of contents,

00:16:39.599 --> 00:16:44.320
put it in a special location, really like some type of output folder, and then I have

00:16:44.320 --> 00:16:46.280
it as a name.

00:16:46.280 --> 00:16:48.039
This is the actual name of the HTML file.

00:16:48.039 --> 00:16:52.960
That's what you ended up seeing in that particular example.

00:16:52.960 --> 00:16:56.719
So the other thing, let's say, for example, you already have your notebook, and everything's

00:16:56.719 --> 00:17:01.679
already rendered, and you don't really want to change it because everything's already

00:17:01.679 --> 00:17:03.280
built in that pipeline.

00:17:03.280 --> 00:17:05.680
But you want to start like a new report.

00:17:05.680 --> 00:17:09.260
And that report needs bits and pieces from that Jupyter notebook.

00:17:09.920 --> 00:17:15.300
So what you can actually do is actually reference a Jupyter notebook, add in some metadata comments,

00:17:15.300 --> 00:17:20.660
and then it can find those bits in the Jupyter notebook and put it into your Quarto document.

00:17:20.660 --> 00:17:24.900
So you don't really have to change any of the code bits if you already have a Jupyter

00:17:24.900 --> 00:17:26.339
notebook pipeline.

00:17:26.339 --> 00:17:29.979
But if you're ready for like, oh, I need to write like another report, and I'm going to

00:17:29.979 --> 00:17:36.319
try this new tool called Quarto, that's another way you can sort of dabble with using Quarto.

00:17:36.319 --> 00:17:37.959
So I have all of these example files.

00:17:37.959 --> 00:17:41.199
If you look at the repository at the bottom, all the example files are there.

00:17:41.199 --> 00:17:44.520
There's a make file, so you can actually see all the commands that get run as well.

00:17:44.520 --> 00:17:49.680
But so first, let's render a notebook just so that all of the output is somewhere.

00:17:49.680 --> 00:17:54.319
And then all you need to do is in the cell of a Jupyter notebook, use regular Quarto

00:17:54.319 --> 00:18:06.479
comments, and you can add bits and pieces of Quarto-like metadata stuff into a Jupyter

00:18:06.479 --> 00:18:07.920
notebook cell.

00:18:07.920 --> 00:18:11.119
And then in your Quarto document, you use a short code.

00:18:11.119 --> 00:18:16.040
You say embed, and then the actual name of the Jupyter notebook, and then literally like

00:18:16.040 --> 00:18:18.479
whatever the label that you have in that cell.

00:18:18.479 --> 00:18:21.280
So right here, label fig.hist.

00:18:21.280 --> 00:18:23.479
That's all you need to put into your Quarto document.

00:18:23.479 --> 00:18:30.119
And then you render the Quarto document just like normal, and you end up with a document

00:18:30.119 --> 00:18:31.119
like this.

00:18:31.119 --> 00:18:35.140
So this is a Quarto document, and all I ended up doing was putting in that short code.

00:18:35.140 --> 00:18:38.680
And this is pulling actually that image straight from the Jupyter notebook and just inserting

00:18:38.680 --> 00:18:40.239
it into my Quarto document.

00:18:40.239 --> 00:18:43.959
And at the bottom, you'll see that there's even a reference to the Jupyter notebook.

00:18:43.959 --> 00:18:48.640
So it does cross-reference back to this is where the original thing came from, and if

00:18:48.640 --> 00:18:51.079
you want, you can download that notebook as well.

00:18:51.079 --> 00:18:53.959
So it's a really nice way of like, hey, I just want to start a report.

00:18:53.959 --> 00:18:58.760
I already have something working, and I don't really want to change that pipeline too much.

00:18:58.760 --> 00:19:03.339
This is a nice little way to like, oh, use Quarto, use it to build your websites or your

00:19:03.339 --> 00:19:09.079
slide decks or something, and just use bits and pieces from your notebook world.

00:19:09.079 --> 00:19:10.459
Last thing I want to talk about is converting.

00:19:10.459 --> 00:19:14.239
So there's another tool called JupyText, and you can use a tool.

00:19:14.239 --> 00:19:19.239
You can use this particular tool to rewrite your R&D document to a Quarto document or

00:19:19.239 --> 00:19:21.800
a Jupyter notebook file to a Quarto document.

00:19:21.800 --> 00:19:24.780
You can use this tool called JupyText to handle that for you.

00:19:24.780 --> 00:19:29.880
So you just end up with your regular QMD file that's been translated over.

00:19:29.880 --> 00:19:33.920
And then QuartoConvert is also another tool that you can use where you can say like, hey,

00:19:33.920 --> 00:19:35.839
here's my Jupyter notebook file.

00:19:35.839 --> 00:19:40.800
Turn this notebook file into a QMD file, and it will do its best to translate everything

00:19:40.800 --> 00:19:41.800
over.

00:19:41.800 --> 00:19:45.939
It does a pretty good job, but you might still have to go do some minor tweaks of things,

00:19:45.939 --> 00:19:47.699
but that's about it.

00:19:47.699 --> 00:19:49.660
But it's a really good way to get started.

00:19:49.660 --> 00:19:52.780
If you already have a notebook and you just want to, I just want to try Quarto, let me

00:19:52.780 --> 00:19:56.339
just convert everything and start from there, this is a really good way of dealing with

00:19:56.339 --> 00:19:58.339
that.

